@NODE "Piktogramme" "Icons"

    Icons

    The tiny graphics used by the Z100-package are directly integrated
    into the program. Optionally there may exist a subdirectory called
    'ICONS',   where   you   can   store   alternative   icons   (e.g.
    MagicWB-Style).  The  internal  graphics  will  be replaced by the
    external icons when you start the program.
    If you have painted a complete Iconset for the  Z100-package,  you
    may send it to me and I will put it into the next release.
    The size of the supported icons is 24x24.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Installation" "Installation"

    Installation

    The installtion  of  Z100  is  imaginable  easy,  because  neither
    external  commands,  function  librarys  nor  a tedious assign are
    needed.
    The included installerskript will normally find out the devicename
    and unit of your SCSI-drive automatically. In order to do this the
    drive must be switched on and it must be mounted. The skript  will
    save  those parameters into an ENV:-variable and also they will be
    filled into the tooltypes of the icons.  Afterwards  the  software
    package will be copied to a choosen location on your harddrive.

    I appreciate to use the script because even experienced users  may
    encounter  problems  when they install the package manually, which
    could be avoided by the usage of the script.

    See also: @{"ToolTypes" LINK "ToolTypes"},@{"CLI-parameters" LINK "CLI-Parameter"},@{"Icons" LINK "Piktogramme"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ZumProg" "Contents of the package"

    Contents of the package

    After installation  the  Z100-directory  will  contain  the  stuff
    mentioned  below.  The  programs  can be started by clicking their
    related  icons  twice.  Some  of  the  programs  use   the   drive
    exclusivly,  so launching those programs twice is not possible. In
    this case a warning requester will appear onto the screen.

    @{"   " LINK "FrameZ100"} FrameZ100 V1.x
    @{"   " LINK "SafeZ100"} SafeZ100 V1.x

    @{"   " LINK "WatchZ100"} WatchZ100 V1.x
    @{"   " LINK "GuessZ100"} GuessZ100 V1.x
    @{"   " LINK "Dosdrivers"} DosDrivers

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FrameZ100" "FrameZ100 V1.x"

    FrameZ100 V1.x

    With this application you can easily copy the whole contents of  a
    ZIP-disk onto you harddrive. The input format of the disk plays no
    part;  you  can   copy   amiga-disk   as   well   as   MSDos-   or
    Macintosh-formatted disks.
    The graphical interface is selfexplaining and should  not  provide
    you  with  problems.  You  can access the password-function of the
    drive also. The only options are for sizing  the  readbuffers  and
    switching the verify-setting.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "SafeZ100" "SafeZ100 V1.x"

    SafeZ100 V1.x

    This little utility is able to change the protection state of  the
    disk.  In  addition  you  can  lock the drive. This is possible by
    deactivating the Ejectbutton until you unlock the drive.
    SafeZ100 will show you only the possible function you can  use  on
    the currently inserted disk.
    For fast access it is reommented to put this program on a  hotkey.
    This   is   possible   if  you  have  installed  an  utility  like
    Toolmanager.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "WatchZ100" "WatchZ100 V1.x"

    WatchZ100 V1.x

    This little utility  may  be  installed  into  "WBStartUp".  After
    restart it is running in the background and checks the drive for a
    diskchange.  If  a   changed   disk   is   password-protected,   a
    user-configurable   program   will  be  lauched  (e.g.  SafeZ100).
    WatchZ100 knows the some special ToolTypes:
    
    RUNCOMMAND - Path and name of the program, which is launched after
                 a valid diskchange (disk must be password-protected).
                 Normally <InstallDir>/@{"SafeZ100" LINK "SafeZ100"}.
    CHECKPORT  - If  SafeZ100  (or  a similar program  which uses  the
                 Z100-Port)  is used,  this tooltype will surpress the
                 upcomming requester, if SafeZ100 is already running.

    If WatchZ100 is installed into the WBStartUp-Folder,  the tooltype
    "DONOTWAIT" must be activated.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ToolTypes" "ToolTypes"

    ToolTypes

    In order to change the tooltypes of an icon, you have to  activate
    the   icon   once   and   select   "Icons/Informations"  from  the
    Workbench-menu. Now you may alter the tooltypes. As an advice, you
    should  not  simply  delete unused tooltypes but you should put it
    into brackets. So you can easily activate the  tooltype  everytime
    and you have always the survey of the supported ones.

    @{"   " LINK "Device"} DEVICE    - Name of your SCSI-device
    @{"   " LINK "Unit"} UNIT      - Unit number of the drive (0-7)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Device" "ToolType/Parameter DEVICE"

    DEVICE

    Here you can enter the name of your SCSI-device, which  controlled
    the  drive.  Normally  it is not necessary, because it should have
    been found out by the installerscript. The declaration of the name
    here  has a higher priority. A change make sense when the drive is
    connected temporary to another controller.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Unit" "ToolType/Parameter UNIT"

    UNIT

    Here you may enter the  unit-number  of  the  drive.  Usually  the
    number  ranged  between 0 and 7, while the external version of the
    drive only allowed the number  5  and  6.  For  more  informations
    please refer to passage about @{"ToolType/parameter DEVICE" LINK "Device"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CLI-Parameter" "CLI-parameters"

    CLI-parameters

    If an application of the Z100-package is started from the  Command
    Line Interpreter (CLI), you can pass some parameters directly. You
    can also enter a question mark behind  the  command  to  list  the
    available  parameters.  Mostly  the  parameters corresponds to the
    supported @{"tooltypes" LINK "ToolTypes"}, which are used from the workbench.

    @{"   " LINK "Device"} DEVICE    - Name of your SCSI-device
    @{"   " LINK "Unit"} UNIT      - Unit number of the drive (0-7)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "GuessZ100" "GuessZ100"

    GuessZ100

    This  little  command  is  used  by  the  Z100-installerscript  to
    recognize  the  ZIP-drive  automatically. It can only be used from
    CLI or as a part of a script. Perhaps there is somebody  who  need
    it elsewhere, so the description of its parameters follows:

    GuessZ100 CHECK/S,LIST/S,SET/S

    CHECK only checks the existence of the drive. It returns errorcode
    0  for  a  valid drive and 5, if and error occured or no drive was
    found.

    LIST shows the parameters of an existing drive or an errormessage.
    New since V1.1: Output  of all  mounted Dos-drives  and the device
    and unit of the last drive.

    SET is especially for the Z100-package. If this parameter is used,
    the  program  creates the environment variable 'Z100DEVICE' when a
    drive was found. This variable contains  the  unitnumber  and  the
    devicename  and may also be used by other programs. If anybody may
    write software which will also use the drive in exclusiv mode,  it
    would be nice, when those program also put up a port called 'Z100'
    and before that look after this portname to prevent collisions.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "DosDrivers" "DosDrivers"

    DosDrivers

    The Z100-package has additional dosdrivers to use disk from Amiga,
    MSDos  and Macintosh-computers. To use the MSDos and Mac-Disks you
    have to install the filesystems CrossDos and CrossMac available at
    your local dealer.

    It  is  possible  to  access  the  images  produced  by  FrameZ100
    directly. In order to do this, three additional dosdrivers for the
    FMS-Device had  been  installed.  If  you  haven't  installed  the
    FMS-Device  on  your  system,  you  should  get the latest version
    (currently V5.01) from Aminet/disk/misc/fmsdisk.lha.

    If you want to use the FMS-Feature you had to  notice  two  facts.
    There  had  to  exist  an  assign  called  'FMS:'  pointing to the
    directory of the images. And the image had to be renamed  'UNITx',
    where 'x' is the unitnumber of the FMS-Unit.

@ENDNODE
